# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: css-variables
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] CSS is designed to enable the separation of content and presentation, including layout, colors, and fonts.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Separation of formatting and content also makes it feasible to present the same markup page in different styles for different rendering methods, such as on-screen, in print, by voice (via speech-based browser or screen reader), and on Braille-based tactile devices.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] CSS also has rules for alternative formatting if the content is accessed on a mobile device.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] The name *cascading* comes from the specified priority scheme to determine which declaration applies if more than one declaration of a property match a particular element.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] This cascading priority scheme is predictable.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] The CSS specifications are maintained by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Internet media type (MIME type) `text/css` is registered for use with CSS by RFC 2318 (March 1998).
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] The W3C operates a free CSS validation service for CSS documents.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] In addition to HTML, other markup languages support the use of CSS including XHTML, plain XML, SVG, and XUL.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] CSS is also used in the GTK widget toolkit.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] CSS has a simple syntax and uses a number of English keywords to specify the names of various style properties.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] A style sheet consists of a list of *rules*.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Each rule or rule-set consists of one or more *selectors*, and a *declaration block*.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] In CSS, *selectors* declare which part of the markup a style applies to by matching tags and attributes in the markup itself.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Classes and IDs are case-sensitive, start with letters, and can include alphanumeric characters, hyphens, and underscores.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] A class may apply to any number of instances of any element.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] An ID may only be applied to a single element.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] One example of a widely used pseudo-class is `:hover`, which identifies content only when the user "points to" the visible element, usually by holding the mouse cursor over it.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] It is appended to a selector as in `a:hover` or `#elementid:hover`.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] A pseudo-class classifies document elements, such as `:link` or `:visited`, whereas a *pseudo-element* makes a selection that may consist of partial elements, such as `::first-line` or `::first-letter`.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Note the distinction between the double-colon notation used for pseudo-elements and the single-colon notation used for pseudo-classes.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Multiple simple selectors may be joined using combinators to specify elements by location, element type, id, class, or any combination thereof.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] The order of the selectors is important.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] For example, `div .myClass {color: red;}` applies to all elements of class myClass that are inside div elements, whereas `.myClass div {color: red;}` applies to all div elements that are inside elements of class myClass.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] This is not to be confused with concatenated identifiers such as `div.myClass {color: red;}` which applies to div elements of class myClass.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] The following table provides a summary of selector syntax indicating usage and the version of CSS that introduced it.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] A declaration block consists of a pair of braces (`{}`) enclosing a semicolon-separated list of *declarations*.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Each declaration itself consists of a *property*, a colon (`:`), and a *value*.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Optional white-space may be around the declaration block, declarations, colons, and semi-colons for readability.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Properties are specified in the CSS standard.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Each property has a set of possible values.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Some properties can affect any type of element, and others apply only to particular groups of elements.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Values may be keywords, such as "center" or "inherit", or numerical values, such as `200px` (200 pixels), `50vw` (50 percent of the viewport width) or 80% (80 percent of the parent element's width).
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Color values can be specified with keywords (e.g.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] `rgb(255, 0, 0)`), RGBA values that specify both color and alpha transparency (e.g.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Non-zero numeric values representing linear measures must include a length unit, which is either an alphabetic code or abbreviation, as in `200px` or `50vw`; or a percentage sign, as in `80%`.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] These eight units were a feature of CSS 1 and retained in all subsequent revisions.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] The proposed CSS Values and Units Module Level 3 will, if adopted as a W3C Recommendation, provide seven further length units: `ch`; `Q`; `rem`; `vh`; `vmax`; `vmin`; and `vw`.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Before CSS, nearly all presentational attributes of HTML documents were contained within the HTML markup.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] That is, all font colors, background styles, element alignments, borders, and sizes had to be explicitly described (often repeatedly) within the HTML.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] CSS lets authors move much of that information to another file, the style sheet, resulting in considerably simpler HTML.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] And additionally, as more and more devices are able to access responsive web pages, different screen sizes and layouts begin to appear.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Customizing a website for each device size is costly and increasingly difficult.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] The modular nature of CSS means that styles can be reused in different parts of a site or even across sites, promoting consistency and efficiency.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] For example, headings (`h1` elements), sub-headings (`h2`), sub-sub-headings (`h3`), etc., are defined structurally using HTML.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] In print and on the screen, choice of font, size, color and emphasis for these elements is *presentational*.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] Before CSS, document authors who wanted to assign such typographic characteristics to, say, all `h2` headings had to repeat HTML presentational markup for each occurrence of that heading type.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] This made documents more complex, larger, and more error-prone and difficult to maintain.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] CSS allows the separation of presentation from structure.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] CSS can define color, font, text alignment, size, borders, spacing, layout and many other typographic characteristics, and can do so independently for on-screen and printed views.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] CSS also defines non-visual styles, such as reading speed and emphasis for aural text readers.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] The W3C has now deprecated the use of all presentational HTML markup.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] The advantages of this may not be immediately clear but the power of CSS becomes more apparent when the style properties are placed in an internal style element or, even better, an external CSS file.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] All `h1` elements in the document will then automatically become red without requiring any explicit code.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] rather than by laboriously going through the document and changing the color for each individual `h1` element.
[src:css-variables/cascading-style-sheets] This further decouples the styling from the HTML document and makes it possible to restyle multiple documents by simply editing a shared external CSS file.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The **cascade** is an algorithm that defines how user agents combine property values originating from different sources.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The cascade defines the origin and layer that takes precedence when declarations in more than one origin, cascade layer, or `@scope` block set a value for a property on an element.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The cascade lies at the core of CSS, as emphasized by the name: ***Cascading*** Style Sheets.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] When a selector matches an element, the property value from the origin with the highest precedence gets applied, even if the selector from a lower precedence origin or layer has greater specificity.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] This article explains what the cascade is and the order in which CSS declarations cascade, covering cascade layers and origin type.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Understanding origin precedence is key to understanding the cascade.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The CSS cascade algorithm's job is to select CSS declarations in order to determine the correct values for CSS properties.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] CSS declarations come from different origin types: **User-agent stylesheets**, **Author stylesheets**, and **User stylesheets**.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Though stylesheets come from these different origins and can be within different layers in each of these origins, they overlap in terms of their default scope; to make this work, the cascade algorithm defines how they interact.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Before addressing the interactions, we'll define some key terms in the next few sections.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] User-agents, or browsers, have basic stylesheets that give default styles to any document.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] These stylesheets are named **user-agent stylesheets**.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Most browsers use actual stylesheets for this purpose, while others simulate them in code.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Some browsers let users modify the user-agent stylesheet, but this is rare and not something that can be controlled.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Although some constraints on user-agent stylesheets are set by the HTML specification, browsers have a lot of latitude: that means some differences exist between browsers.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] To simplify the development process, Web developers may use a CSS reset stylesheet, such as normalize.css, which sets common properties values to a known state for all browsers before beginning to make alterations to suit their specific needs.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Unless the user-agent stylesheet includes an `!important` next to a property, making it "important", styles declared by author styles, including a reset stylesheet, take precedence over the user-agent styles, regardless of the specificity of the associated selector.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] In most browsers, the user (or reader) of the website can choose to override styles using a custom **user stylesheet** designed to tailor the experience to the user's wishes.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Depending on the user agent, user styles can be configured directly or added via browser extensions.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The cascade order is based on origin type.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The cascade within each origin type is based on the declaration order of cascade layers within that type.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] For all origins - user-agent, author, or user - styles can be declared within or outside of named or anonymous layers.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] When declared using `layer`, `layer()` or `@layer`, styles are placed into the specified named layer, or into an anonymous layer if no name is provided.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Styles declared outside of a layer are treated as being part of an anonymous last declared layer.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Let's take a look at cascading origin type before diving into cascade layers within each origin type.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The cascading algorithm determines how to find the value to apply for each property for each document element.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] **Origin and importance**: Then it sorts these rules according to their importance, that is, whether or not they are followed by `!important`, and by their origin.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] **Specificity**: In case of equality with an origin, the specificity of a rule is considered to choose one value or another.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The specificity of the selectors are compared, and the declaration with the highest specificity wins.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] **Scoping proximity**: When two selectors in the origin layer with precedence have the same specificity, the property value within scoped rules with the smallest number of hops up the DOM hierarchy to the scope root wins.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] See How `@scope` conflicts are resolved for more details and an example.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] **Order of appearance**: In the origin with precedence, if there are competing values for a property that are in style block matching selectors of equal specificity and scoping proximity, the last declaration in the style order is applied.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Property values set by animation `@keyframes` are more important than all normal styles (those with no `!important` set).
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Property values being set in a `transition` take precedence over all other values set, even those marked with `!important`.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The cascade algorithm is applied *before* the specificity algorithm, meaning if `:root p { color: red;}` is declared in the user stylesheet (row 2) and a less specific `p {color: blue;}` is in the author stylesheet (row 3), the paragraphs will be blue.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] In this case, declarations inside `li` and `.specific` rules should apply.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Due to lack of *relevance* based on its media type, it is removed from consideration.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] No declaration is marked as `!important`, so the precedence order is author stylesheets over user stylesheets over user-agent stylesheet.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Based on *origin and importance*, the `1em` from the user stylesheet and the `10px` from the user-agent stylesheet are removed from consideration.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Note that even though the user style on `.specific` of `1em` has a higher specificity, it's a normal declaration in a user stylesheet.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] As such, it has a lower precedence than any author styles, and gets removed by the origin and importance step of the algorithm before specificity even comes into play.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The last one, the `5px` is part of a cascade layer.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Normal declarations in layers have lower precedence than normal styles not in a layer within the same origin type.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] This is also removed by step 2 of the algorithm, *origin and importance*.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] This leaves the `0` and the `3px`, which both have the same selector, hence the same *specificity*.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Neither of them are inside a `@scope` block, so scoping proximity does not come into play in this example either.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The second one, the last of the two unlayered author styles, wins.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The table in Cascading order provided a precedence order overview.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The table summarized the user-agent, user, and author origin type styles in two lines each with "origin type - normal" and "origin type - !important".
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The precedence within each origin type is more nuanced.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Styles can be contained within layers within their origin type, and, with author styles, there is also the issue of where inline styles land in the cascade order.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The order in which layers are declared is important in determining precedence.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Normal styles in a layer take precedence over styles declared in prior layers; with normal styles declared outside of any layer taking precedence over normal layered styles regardless of specificity.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] In this example, the author used CSS's `@import` rule to import five external stylesheets within a `<style>` information element.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] In the CSS code block above, three cascade layers named "A", "B", and "C", were created, in that order.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Three stylesheets were imported directly into layers and two were imported without creating or being assigned to a layer.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The "All unlayered styles" in the list below (normal author style precedence - order 4) includes styles from these two stylesheets and the additional unlayered CSS style blocks.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] In all origin types, normal styles contained in layers have the lowest precedence.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] In our example, the normal styles associated with the first declared layer (A) have lower precedence than normal styles in the second declared layer (B), which have lower precedence than normal styles in the third declared layer (C).
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] These layered styles have lower precedence than all normal unlayered styles, which includes normal styles from `unlayeredStyles.css`, `moreUnlayeredStyles.css`, and the `color` of `p` in the `<style>` itself.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] If any layered styles in A, B, or C have selectors with higher specificity matching an element, similar to `:root body p { color: black; }`, it doesn't matter.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Those declarations are removed from consideration because of *origin*; normal layered styles have less precedence than normal unlayered styles.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] If, however, the more specific selector `:root body p { color: black; }` was found in `unlayeredStyles.css`, as both *origin and importance* have the same precedence, *specificity* would mean the more specific, black declaration would win.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The layer order of precedence is inverted for styles declared as `!important`.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Important declarations found in a layer take precedence over important declarations found outside of a layer.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Important declarations found in the first layer (A) take precedence over important declarations found in layer B, which take precedence over important declarations found in layer C, which take precedence over important declarations found outside of a layer.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Only relevant to author styles are inline styles, declared with the `style` attribute.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Normal inline styles take precedence over any other normal author styles, no matter the specificity of the selector.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] If `line-height: 2;` were declared in a `:root body p` selector block in any of the five imported stylesheets, the line height would still be `1.6`.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Normal inline styles do not take precedence over animated or transitioned properties.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Important inline styles take precedence over all other author styles, regardless of whether they are important, inline, or layered.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Important inline styles also take precedence over animated properties, but not transitioned properties.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The origin type precedence order is inverted for important styles.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Important styles declared outside of any cascade layer have lower precedence than those declared as part of a layer.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Important styles that come in early layers take precedence over important styles declared in subsequent cascade layers.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Even though the red is declared first and has a less specific selector, because unlayered CSS takes precedence over layered CSS, the paragraph will be red.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Had we included an inline style on the paragraph setting it to a different color, such as `<p style="color: black">`, the paragraph would be black.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The `!important` in the earliest declared layer takes precedence over subsequent layers and unlayered important declarations.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] If the inline style contained `!important`, such as `<p style="color: black !important">`, again the paragraph would be black.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Inline importance does take precedence over all other author declared `!important` declarations, no matter the specificity.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Styles that are transitioning take precedence over all important styles, no matter who or how they are declared.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Only CSS property/value pair declarations participate in the cascade.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] CSS at-rule descriptors don't participate in the cascade and HTML presentational attributes are not part of the cascade.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] CSS at-rules containing entities other than declarations, such as a `@font-face` rule containing *descriptors*, don't participate in the cascade.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] For the most part, the properties and descriptors defined in at-rules don't participate in the cascade.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Only at-rules as a whole participate in the cascade.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] For example, within a `@font-face` rule, font names are identified by `font-family` descriptors.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] If several `@font-face` rules with the same descriptor are defined, only the most appropriate `@font-face`, as a whole, is considered.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] If more than one are identically appropriate, the entire `@font-face` declarations are compared using steps 1, 2, and 4 of the algorithm (there is no specificity when it comes to at-rules).
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] While the declarations contained in most at-rules — such as those in `@media`, `@document`, or `@supports` — participate in the cascade, the at-rule may make an entire selector not relevant, as we saw with the print style in the basic example.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Declarations in `@keyframes` don't participate in the cascade.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] As with `@font-face`, only the `@keyframes` as a whole is selected via the cascade algorithm.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The precedence order of animation is described below.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] When it comes to `@import`, the `@import` doesn't participate itself in the cascade, but all of the imported styles do participate.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] If the `@import` defines a named or anonymous layer, the contents of the imported stylesheet are placed into the specified layer.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] All other CSS imported with `@import` is treated as the last declared layer.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Finally, `@charset` obeys specific algorithms and isn't affected by the cascade algorithm.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Presentational attributes are attributes in the source document that can affect styling.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] For example, when included, the deprecated `align` attribute sets the alignment on several HTML elements and the `fill` attribute defines the color used to paint SVG shapes and text and defines the final state for SVG animations.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] While they are author styles, presentational attributes do not participate in the cascade.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Presentational attributes cannot be declared `!important`.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] CSS animations, using `@keyframes` at-rules, define animations between states.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] `@keyframes` don't cascade, meaning that at any given time CSS takes values from only one single set of `@keyframes` and never mixes multiple ones.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] If multiple sets of `@keyframes` are defined with the same animation name, the last defined set in the origin and layer with the greatest precedence is used.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] Other `@keyframes` are ignored, even if they animate different properties.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] In this example, there are three separate animation declaration named `repeatedName`.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] When `animation: infinite 5s alternate repeatedName` is applied to the paragraph, only one animation is applied: the keyframe animation defined in the unlayered CSS takes precedence over the layered keyframe animation declarations based on origin and layer precedence order.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] In this example, only the element's font size will be animated.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] After your content has finished altering styles, it may find itself in a situation where it needs to restore them to a known state.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] This may happen in cases of animations, theme changes, and so forth.
[src:css-variables/css-cascade-cascade] The CSS property `all` lets you quickly set (almost) everything in CSS back to a known state.
[src:css-variables/css-env] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:css-variables/css-env] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The **`env()`** CSS function can be used to insert the value of a user-agent defined environment variable into your CSS.
[src:css-variables/css-env] A `<custom-ident>` specifying the name of the environment variable to be inserted.
[src:css-variables/css-env] If the name provided represents an array-like environment variable, the name is followed by `<integer>` values identifying the specific instance the name is referencing.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The safe distance from the top, right, bottom, or left inset edge of the viewport, defining where it is safe to place content into without risking it being cut off by the shape of a non‑rectangular display.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The four values form a rectangle, inside which all content is visible.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The values are `0` if the viewport is a rectangle and no features — such as toolbars or dynamic keyboards — are occupying viewport space; otherwise, it is a `px` value greater than `0`.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The static maximum values of their dynamic `safe-area-inset-*` variable counterparts when all dynamic user interface features are retracted.
[src:css-variables/css-env] While the `safe-area-inset-*` values change as the currently-visible content area changes, the `safe-area-max-inset-*` values are constants.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The dimensions of a visible `titlebar-area-*` area.
[src:css-variables/css-env] These variables are available when using the `window-controls-overlay` `display_override` manifest field.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The variables' values can be used to ensure content doesn't overlap window control buttons (that is, minimize, maximize, and close) with progressive web apps (PWA) installed on desktop devices.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The insets from the edge of the viewport and dimensions of the device's on-screen virtual keyboard.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The user's preferred font scaling factor, a number set in browser or OS-level preferences.
[src:css-variables/css-env] This can be used to size content proportionally to browser or OS-set font sizes.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The dimensions and offset positions of specific viewport segments.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The `viewport-segment-*` keyword is followed by two space-separated `<integer>` values that indicate the segment's horizontal and vertical position, or indices.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The viewport-segment keywords are only defined when the viewport is made up of two or more segments, as with foldable or hinged devices.
[src:css-variables/css-env] A fallback value to be inserted if the environment variable referenced in the first argument does not exist.
[src:css-variables/css-env] Everything after the first comma is deemed to be the fallback value.
[src:css-variables/css-env] This can be a single value, another `env()` function, or a comma-separated list of values.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The `env()` function is used to insert the value of a globally-scoped, user-agent-defined environment variable into your CSS.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The `env()` function can be used as a property value or in place of any part of a property value or descriptor (for example, in Media query rules).
[src:css-variables/css-env] The function accepts an `<environment-variable>` as its first argument.
[src:css-variables/css-env] This is a case-sensitive `<custom-ident>` equal to the name of the environment variable to be substituted, but it can also include additional space-separated values if required.
[src:css-variables/css-env] For example, `env(viewport-segment-width 0 0)` would return the width of the top or left segment in the case of a device with multiple viewport segments.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The second argument, if provided, is the fallback value, which is used if the environment variable referenced in the first argument is not supported or doesn't exist.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The fallback can be another environment variable, even with its own fallback.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The syntax of the fallback is similar to the fallback syntax of the `var()` function used to insert CSS custom properties in that it allows for multiple commas.
[src:css-variables/css-env] Anything between the first comma and the end of the function is considered the fallback value.
[src:css-variables/css-env] However, if the `env()` function is used within a property value or descriptor that doesn't include commas, a fallback value that includes commas will not be valid.
[src:css-variables/css-env] A property or descriptor containing a syntactically valid `env()` function is assumed to be valid at parse time, when the browser first reads and interprets the downloaded CSS text.
[src:css-variables/css-env] It is only syntax-checked at compute time, after each `env()` function has been substituted with its browser-provided value (or the fallback value if the environment variable passed as the first parameter is not a recognized environment variable name).
[src:css-variables/css-env] If the value is invalid and no fallback is provided, the property or descriptor containing the `env()` function is invalid at computed-value time.
[src:css-variables/css-env] When an `env()` substitution is invalid, and an invalid fallback is included, or the fallback is omitted, the declaration is not ignored.
[src:css-variables/css-env] Instead, the initial or inherited value of the property is used.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The property is set to a new value, but it may not be the expected one.
[src:css-variables/css-env] Originally provided by the iOS browser to allow developers to place their content in a safe area of the viewport, and not be obscured by device notches or rounded corners, the `safe-area-inset-*` values can be used to help ensure content is visible to viewers.
[src:css-variables/css-env] This feature was later expanded beyond its initial purpose to enable use cases such as stopping device notifications from covering up some of the app user interface.
[src:css-variables/css-env] Another use case for `env()` variables is for desktop Progressive web apps (PWAs) that use the Window Controls Overlay feature to take advantage of the full application window surface area.
[src:css-variables/css-env] Using the `titlebar-area-*` values values, developers can position elements where the title bar would have been and ensure content is not obscured by window control buttons.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The `viewport-segment-*` variable names can be used to set your containers to fit neatly into the available segments of a multi-viewport-segment device such as a hinged or foldable device.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The integers following the `viewport-segment-*` name indicate which segment of the multiple segments the environment variable is referencing.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The `preferred-text-scale` variable can be used to size website text or other UI features proportionally to browser or OS-set font sizes.
[src:css-variables/css-env] Sizes can also be set to be proportional to browser or OS-level font size by including `<meta name="text-scale" content="scale">` inside the document `<head>`.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The `<meta>` tag should be used in favor of the `env(preferred-text-scale)` when possible, as the `<meta>` tag is supported across a wider range of platforms and is also simpler to use.
[src:css-variables/css-env] For example, in the case of the `viewport-segment-*` variables, the variable names are passed to the `env()` function along with two integers indicating the indices of the segment to return the value for.
[src:css-variables/css-env] These values are both integers of `0` or greater.
[src:css-variables/css-env] (Two device segment layouts; in a horizontal layout, 0 0 is the first segment and 1 0 is the second segment.
[src:css-variables/css-env] See the Viewport segment API demo for a full working demo (source code).
[src:css-variables/css-env] Also check out Using the Viewport Segments API for a full demo explanation.
[src:css-variables/css-env] In the following example, `env()` is used to ensure that fixed app toolbar buttons are not obscured by device notifications appearing at the bottom of the screen.
[src:css-variables/css-env] On the desktop `safe-area-inset-bottom` is `0`.
[src:css-variables/css-env] However, in devices that display notifications at the bottom of the screen, such as iOS, it contains a value that leaves space for the notification to display.
[src:css-variables/css-env] This can then be used in the value for `padding-bottom` to create a gap that appears natural on that device.
[src:css-variables/css-env] We set `position: sticky` to stick the footer to the bottom of the viewport.
[src:css-variables/css-env] We then use the `padding` shorthand to add padding to the footer.
[src:css-variables/css-env] We include the value of the `safe-area-inset-bottom` environment value to an initial `1em` of bottom padding.
[src:css-variables/css-env] A larger black area will display on devices that have a positive value for this variable, ensuring the buttons in the footer are never obscured.
[src:css-variables/css-env] This example makes use of the optional second parameter of `env()`, which provides a fallback value in case the environment variable is not available.
[src:css-variables/css-env] We set a `width` of `300px` and a `border`.
[src:css-variables/css-env] We then add `padding`, using the `env()` function with a fallback for the size of the padding on each side.
[src:css-variables/css-env] We intentionally set an invalid value for the left padding (remember, environment variable names are case-sensitive), to demonstrate the use of the fallback value.
[src:css-variables/css-env] In the following example, `env()` ensures that content displayed in a desktop Progressive Web App that uses the Window Controls Overlay API is not obscured by the operating system's window control buttons.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The `titlebar-area-*` values define a rectangle where the title bar would normally have been displayed.
[src:css-variables/css-env] On devices that do not support the Window Controls Overlay feature, such as mobile devices, the fallback values are used.
[src:css-variables/css-env] The Viewport segment API demo and Using the Viewport Segments API guide provides a demonstration and explanation of using the `env()` function with the `viewport-segments-*` environment variables.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] The **`inherit`** CSS keyword causes the element to take the computed value of the property from its parent element.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] It can be applied to any CSS property, including the CSS shorthand property `all`.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] For inherited properties, this reinforces the default behavior, and is only needed to override another rule.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] In this example, we demonstrate the effect of the `inherit` keyword by comparing two paragraphs with nested elements: the inline elements in one use their browser default styles, while those in the other inherit individual property values from their parent.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] We include two identical paragraphs with several inline elements.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] We don't style the inline elements in the first paragraph, so they use their default browser styles.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] In the second paragraph, we set properties on each inline element to `inherit`, so they get the computed styles from the parent `<p>` element.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] In this example, we use the same HTML as in the previous example to demonstrate the issues that can occur when the `inherit` keyword is applied to all properties.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] In the second paragraph, instead of setting individual properties to `inherit`, we set the `all` property on all inline elements to `inherit`, so they all get computed styles from their parent `<p>`.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] Notice how the inline element inherit all the properties of the parent `<p>`, including the paragraph's block-level `display` value.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] This is likely not the effect you would want.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] This example demonstrates how the `inherit` keyword can be used to exclude selected elements from a color rule, allowing them to use their parent's color instead.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] We include some semantically structured content.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] We set the text color of the `<main>` element to `blue` and all `<h2>` elements to `green` in `monospace` font.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] The `<h2>` elements inside a `<section>` are set to `inherit` their parent's text color.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] However, if they are nested in a `<section>` element, they inherit their color from their parent, which is `blue` within `<main>`.
[src:css-variables/css-inherit] The default text color is black otherwise.
[src:css-variables/css-var] It’s been available across browsers since April 2017.
[src:css-variables/css-var] The **`var()`** CSS function can be used to insert the value of a custom property (sometimes called a "CSS variable") instead of any part of a value of another property.
[src:css-variables/css-var] The `var()` function cannot be used in property names, selectors or anything else besides property values.
[src:css-variables/css-var] The first argument to the function is the name of the custom property to be substituted.
[src:css-variables/css-var] An optional second argument to the function serves as a fallback value.
[src:css-variables/css-var] The fallback is used when the referenced custom property doesn't have a usable value — what the specification calls the guaranteed-invalid value.
[src:css-variables/css-var] If the custom property is registered with `@property` using a non-universal `syntax` and an `initial-value`, that initial value is substituted when no other declaration applies.
[src:css-variables/css-var] The fallback is *not* used in that case.
[src:css-variables/css-var] The other CSS-wide keywords — `inherit`, `unset`, `revert`, `revert-layer`, and `revert-rule` — behave in the same way when set as a custom property value as they do on any other property.
[src:css-variables/css-var] They can resolve the custom property to an inherited or previously-cascaded value rather than to the guaranteed-invalid value, so they don't necessarily trigger the fallback.
[src:css-variables/css-var] For example, if `--foo` is set to `revert-layer` in one cascade layer and to a color in another layer, `var(--foo)` resolves to the color value instead of using the fallback.
[src:css-variables/css-var] The syntax of the fallback, like that of custom properties, allows commas.
[src:css-variables/css-var] For example, `var(--foo, red, blue)` defines a fallback of `red, blue`; that is, anything between the first comma and the end of the function is considered a fallback value.
[src:css-variables/css-var] A custom property's name represented by an identifier that starts with two dashes.
[src:css-variables/css-var] Custom properties are solely for use by authors and users; CSS will never give them a meaning beyond what is presented here.
[src:css-variables/css-var] A fallback value for the custom property, used when the referenced custom property has the guaranteed-invalid value (see the Syntax section above for the conditions under which this happens).
[src:css-variables/css-var] This value may contain any character except some characters with special meaning like newlines, unmatched closing brackets, i.e., `)`, `]`, or `}`, top-level semicolons, or exclamation marks.
[src:css-variables/css-var] The fallback value can itself be a custom property using the `var()` syntax.
[src:css-variables/css-var] If the fallback value is omitted, and the custom property has the guaranteed-invalid value, the `var()` function resolves to an invalid value.
[src:css-variables/css-var] Here, the value of the `background-color` property has been set via the custom property `--main-bg-color`.
[src:css-variables/css-var] So the background color of the HTML body will be pink.
[src:css-variables/css-var] In this example, the background color of the HTML body will be pink even though the custom property is set later.
[src:css-variables/css-var] The background color of the HTML body will be pink in this case even though the custom property is declared in another file.
[src:css-variables/css-var] Since `--header-color` isn't set, the text "Header" will be blue, the fallback value.
[src:css-variables/css-var] Since `--main-bg-color` isn't set, the body's `background-color` will fall back to `--backup-bg-color`, which is teal.
[src:css-variables/css-var] When this happens, the property is treated as if it has value `unset`.
[src:css-variables/css-var] This is because variables can't "fail early" like other syntax errors can, so by the time the user agent realizes a property value is invalid, it has already thrown away the other cascaded values.
[src:css-variables/css-var] Note how the paragraphs using `var()` are reset to the default black, but the paragraph with an invalid literal color is still red, because the `color: 20px` declaration is simply ignored.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Complex websites have very large amounts of CSS, and this often results in a lot of repeated CSS values.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] For example, it's common to see the same color used in hundreds of different places in stylesheets.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Changing a color that's been duplicated in many places requires a search and replace across all rules and CSS files.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Custom properties allow a value to be defined in one place, then referenced in multiple other places so that it's easier to work with.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Another benefit is readability and semantics.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] For example, `--main-text-color` is easier to understand than the hexadecimal color `#00ff00`, especially if the color is used in different contexts.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Custom properties defined using two dashes (`--`) are subject to the cascade and inherit their value from their parent.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The `@property` at-rule allows more control over the custom property and lets you specify whether it inherits its value from a parent, what the initial value is, and the type constraints that should apply.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] In CSS, you can declare a custom property using two dashes as a prefix for the property name, or by using the `@property` at-rule.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The following sections describe how to use these two methods.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] A custom property prefixed with two dashes begins with `--`, followed by the property name (e.g., `--my-property`), and a property value that can be any valid CSS value.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Like any other property, this is written inside a ruleset.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The selector given to the ruleset (`<section>` elements in the example above) defines the scope in which the custom property can be used.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] This doesn't always have to be the case: you maybe have a good reason for limiting the scope of your custom properties.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The `@property` at-rule allows you to be more expressive with the definition of a custom property with the ability to associate a type with the property, set default values, and control inheritance.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] If you want to define or work with custom properties in JavaScript instead of directly in CSS, there is a corresponding API for this purpose.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] You can read about how this works in the CSS Properties and Values API page.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Let's start with some HTML that we would like to apply some styles to.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] We will use the following CSS to style a few different elements based on their classes (some layout rules are not shown below so we can focus on colors).
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] There's an opportunity to use custom properties to replace repetitive values across these rules.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] For some CSS declarations, it is possible to declare this higher in the cascade and let CSS inheritance solve this problem.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] For non-trivial projects, this is not always possible.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] This leads to the same result as the previous example, yet allows for one canonical declaration of the desired property value (`--main-bg-color: teal;`), which is very useful if you want to change the value across the entire project later.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] A custom property defined using two dashes `--` instead of `@property` always inherits the value of its parent.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] One aspect of custom properties that the examples above demonstrate is that they don't behave exactly like variables in other programming languages.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The value is computed where it is needed, not stored and reused in other places of a stylesheet.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] For instance, you cannot set a property's value and expect to retrieve the value in a sibling's descendant's rule.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The property is only set for the matching selector and its descendants.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The `@property` at-rule lets you explicitly state whether the property inherits or not.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The following example creates a custom property using the `@property` at-rule.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Inheritance is disabled, there's a `<color>` data type defined, and an initial value of `teal`.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The parent element sets `--box-color` to a value of `green` and uses `--box-color` as a value for its background color.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The child element also uses `background-color: var(--box-color)`, and we would expect it to have the color `green` if inheritance was enabled (or if it was defined using the double dash syntax).
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] You can define fallback values for custom properties using the `var()` function, and the `initial-value` of the `@property` at-rule.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Using the `var()` function, you can define multiple **fallback values** when the given variable is not yet defined; this can be useful when working with Custom Elements and Shadow DOM.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The first argument to the function is the name of the custom property.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The second argument to the function is an optional fallback value, which is used as the substitution value when the referenced custom property is invalid.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The function accepts two parameters, assigning everything following the first comma as the second parameter.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] If the second parameter is invalid, the fallback will fail.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Including a custom property as a fallback, as seen in the second example above (`var(--my-var, var(--my-background, pink))`), is the correct way to provide more than one fallback with `var()`.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] You should be aware of the performance impact of this method, however, as it takes more time to parse through the nested variables.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Aside from using `var()`, the `initial-value` defined in the `@property` at-rule can be used as a fallback mechanism.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] In fact, we've already seen this in the `@property` inheritance section.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The following example sets an initial value of `--box-color` to `teal` using the `@property` at-rule.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] In the ruleset following the at-rule, we want to set `--box-color` to `pink`, but there's a typo in the value name.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The same is true for the third `<div>` where we've used `2rem` for the custom property that's expecting a valid `<color>` value.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Each CSS property can be assigned a defined set of values.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] If you try to assign a value to a property that is outside its set of valid values, it's considered *invalid*.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] When the browser encounters an invalid value for a regular CSS property (for example, a value of `16px` for the `color` property), it discards the declaration, and elements are assigned the values that they would have had if the declaration did not exist.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] However, when the values of custom properties are parsed, the browser doesn't yet know where they will be used, so it must consider nearly all values as *valid*.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Unfortunately, these valid values can be used, via the `var()` functional notation, in a context where they might not make sense.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Properties and custom variables can lead to invalid CSS statements, leading to the concept of *valid at computed time*.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] When the browser encounters an invalid `var()` substitution, then the initial or inherited value of the property is used.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] This example is just like the last one, except we use a custom property.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] The browser substitutes the value of `--text-color` in place of `var(--text-color)`, but `16px` is not a valid property value for `color`.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] Set the value to its **default initial value**, which is black.
[src:css-variables/using-css-custom-properties] To use the values of custom properties in JavaScript, it is just like standard properties.
